"title": "1347: covenant, God's with Noah",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "1347",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>God's confirmation of, and commitment to maintain, his relationship with the natural order- implicit in the act of creation- whereby he promised never again to destroy the earth with a flood. This divine pledge, given unconditionally to Noah and to every living creature on earth, was accompanied by the sign of the rainbow.</p>\n<h2>The occasion of the covenant</h2>\n<h3>The flood as divine judgment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:17\">GEN 6:17</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:5-Gen6:7\">GEN 6:5–6:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:11-Gen6:13\">GEN 6:11–6:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Pet2:5\">2PE 2:5</a></p>\n<h3>God's promise of salvation to Noah and his family</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:18\">GEN 6:18</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:23\">GEN 7:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:1\">GEN 8:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:15-Gen8:17\">GEN 8:15–8:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb11:7\">HEB 11:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet3:20\">1PE 3:20</a></p>\n<h3>God's promise never again to destroy the earth with a flood</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:11\">GEN 9:11</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:21\">GEN 8:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa54:9\">ISA 54:9</a></p>\n<h2>The sign of the covenant</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:13\">GEN 9:13</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:14-Gen9:17\">GEN 9:14–9:17</a></p>\n<h2>A universal covenant</h2>\n<h3>God's relationship with every living creature</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:8-Gen9:10\">GEN 9:8–9:10</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:1-Gen7:3\">GEN 7:1–7:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek34:25\">EZK 34:25</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:18\">HOS 2:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech11:10\">ZEC 11:10</a></p>\n<h3>God's relationship with the natural order</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:22\">GEN 8:22</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer33:25-Jer33:26\">JER 33:25–33:26</a></strong> <em>God's relationship with the created order is here expressed as a covenant. It is probable that this is a reference to the Noahic covenant through which the implicit relationship between Creator and creation was confirmed.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen1:14\">GEN 1:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen1:31\">GEN 1:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen2:1\">GEN 2:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps74:16-Ps74:17\">PSA 74:16–74:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer5:24\">JER 5:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer33:20-Jer33:21\">JER 33:20–33:21</a></p>\n<h2>An everlasting covenant</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:16\">GEN 9:16</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:12\">GEN 9:12</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa24:5\">ISA 24:5</a></strong> <em>The reference here is to the Noahic covenant. Though this covenant was unconditional, the prohibition of bloodshed--often described as bringing pollution to the land--was associated with it. There may be, also, a wider reference to the effects of mankind's disregard for the norms laid down at creation.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen9:6\">GEN 9:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num35:33\">NUM 35:33</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa26:21\">ISA 26:21</a></p>",
